<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="12" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="12">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="12">NEW BRUNSWICK: Charlotte Co.: Grand Manan archipelago, Kent Island, 23 July 2012, M. Steck, balsam fir forest, sweeping (1, KIC). NOVA SCOTIA: Annapolis Co.: Durland Lake, 21 June 2003, P. Dollin, hemlock/balsam fir/black spruce forest (120+ years), bracket fungi on white birch (1, NSMC).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="3" pageNumber="12" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="12">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="12">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Mycetophagidae" genus="Mycetophagus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mycetophagus serrulatus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serrulatus">Mycetophagus serrulatus</taxonomicName>
Casey is newly recorded in New Brunswick. The species was reported from Nova Scotia by 
<bibRefCitation author="Dollin, PE" editor="Majka, CG" journalOrPublisher="Biodiversity, Biosystematics, and Ecology of Canadian Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="21" pagination="291 - 336" title="Saproxylic beetle (Coleoptera) communities and forest management practices in coniferous stands in southwest Nova Scotia" url="http://pensoftonline.net/zookeys/index.php/journal/article/view/15/44" volume="2" year="2008">Dollin et al. (2008)</bibRefCitation>
(Fig. 1). Both specimens were found in coniferous forests, one on a polypore fungus growing on a white birch (
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Betula papyrifera" order="Fagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="papyrifera">Betula papyrifera</taxonomicName>
Marshall). 
<bibRefCitation author="Cline, AR" journalOrPublisher="Southeastern Naturalist" pageId="12" pageNumber="21" pagination="409 - 420" title="Coleoptera associated with the oyster mushroom, Pleurotus ostreatus Fries, in North America." volume="4" year="2005">Cline and Leshen (2005)</bibRefCitation>
recorded it from oyster mushroom (
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Pleurotaceae" genus="Pleurotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Pleurotus ostreatus" order="Agaricales" pageId="3" pageNumber="12" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="ostreatus">Pleurotus ostreatus</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
